tle> Re: aye!</span><hr size=1> I used FOL to solo a sand giant the other day...<br><br>Beat on it until I was down to two bubbles, then FOL'd it.  While it was running, I Ghealed myself.  Got two casts off before it came back.  <br><br>Worked like a charm. <p><div align="center"><font size="2">Aragir Lancot<BR><BR><font size="1">"One man plus the truth equals a majority."<BR>Cerivel tells you, 'Hehe grats on scaring off a level 56 giant that hits for 360'<BR><BR>Paladin of the 49th shield<BR><a href="http://www.emeraldis.com/~booraembj/">Exiles</a>, Xegony<BR></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uvladimirrdbenefiece.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Vladimirr DBenefiece</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.execpc.com/~jwnrski/shield.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Holy Defender</span><br>  Posts: 529<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(4/3/02 6:43:52 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fpaladinsofnorrathgeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=15143.topic&index=9>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www.execpc.com/~jwnrski/vladsig.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: aye!</span><hr size=1> I agree with Wulfhere.  We've both written extensively on the use of the spell.<br><br>I'll try to type up a guide again - this time I'm saving it as a text file on my HDD :P <p><font color="0000aa"><h5>Vladimirr D'Benefiece<br>Officer, Order of the White Dragon<br>Deepwater Knight<br>In Service of our Good and Gracious Oceanlord, Prexus<br>Bristlebane Server<br><a href = "http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=17434">Click here for equipment listing</a><br></h5></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uvladimirrdbenefiece.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Vladimirr DBenefiece</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.execpc.com/~jwnrski/shield.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Holy Defender</span><br>  Posts: 530<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(4/3/02 7:24:21 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fpaladinsofnorrathgeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=15143.topic&index=10>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www.execpc.com/~jwnrski/vladsig.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: aye!</span><hr size=1> <center><font color="0077ff"><hr><h3>A Paladin's guide to </font><font color="ffffff""><i>Flash of Light</i></h3><h6></font><br><font color="0077ff">by Vladimirr D'Benefiece and Wulfhere Hausakliufr</h6><hr></font></center><br><br>Flash of Light (FoL) is one of the most useful spells in the Paladin's book.  Unfortunately, it is also one of the most underrated and underappreciated spells as well.  I hope that through this guide, more Paladins will come to learn, use, and love it.<br><br>First, the basics of how Flash of Light works.<br><br>When Flash of Light is cast on an NPC...<br><br><table border = 0 cellspacing = 20><tr><td><i>If the person highest on the NPC's hate list is in melee range...</td><td>...the NPC will attack that person.</td></tr><tr><td><i>If the person highest on the NPC's hate list is <b>not</b> in melee range...</td><td>...the NPC will flee along its flight path, as if it were feared.</td></tr></table><br>Drawing conclusions from these very basic statments, we see that Flash of Light has 4 main uses.<br><br><ol><br><font color="ff3333"><li><b>Aggro Management</b></li></font><br><br>By far the most useful application of Flash of Light is taunting.  This spell is one of the most, if not <i>the</i> most important tool in the Paladin's Aggro Management toolbox.<br><br>Flash of Light generates a very large taunt.  It has a quick recast of 3 seconds.  It only costs 12 mana.  It is rarely resisted, and even when resisted acts as an excellent taunt.  Another little known fact is that it removes 5 ATK from its target.  While 5 ATK is not much, every little bit helps.<br><br>Looking at these points, it's readily apparent why Flash of Light is such a useful spell.  As a comparison, another popular taunt spell (Stun), costs 35 mana (over 3 times as much!), and has a very slow recast (12 seconds).  Not to mention using Flash of Light to draw aggro leaves Stun available to interrupt casters.<br><br>The catch to Flash of Light, of course, is the second clause  - "If the person highest on the NPC's hate list is <b>not</b> in melee range, the NPC will flee along its flight path, as if it were feared".<br><br>A Paladin using only Flash of Light to draw aggro would be doing so at much personal risk.  All it takes is for one caster to over-nuke, and place themselves at the top of the hate list.  Of course, if the monster is blinded, and the caster is out of melee range, it's going to take off like a bat out of hell.<br><br>Do not think of Flash of Light as a way to <i>get</i> aggro.  Think of Flash of Light as a mana-and-time efficient way to <i>KEEP</i> aggro.  When an NPC comes to the group, start with a few rounds of battle, intermingled with Stuns, Taunts, Bashes, Disarms, anything to get as high on the hate list as possible.  Once you've established yourself at the top of the hate list, start casting Flash of Light.  You'll save a lot of mana, especially over a long fight, and your stuns will be available to stop the NPC from casting.<br><br><font color="ff3333"><li><b>Fear (Offensive)</b></li></font><br><br>Flash of Light can also be used to mimic the Fear spell.  This allows a Paladin and his partner to slay things that would normally tear the two to shreds.<br><br>In this case, you use the second clause to your advantage: "If the person highest on the NPC's hate list is <b>not</b> in melee range, the NPC will flee along its flight path, as if it were feared".<br><br>The key to this is having a partner.  Preferably a partner that can slow movement speed (Snare, Darkness, etc...)  When pulling, the Paladin should quickly establish himself at the top of the hate list.  This can easily be accomplished by rooting the mob, stepping back, and repeatedly casting Flash of Light until Root wears off.<br><br>Once Root wears off, keep Flash of Light applied every time it wears off.  Your partner should follow the fleeing NPC and melee it to death.  If your partner somehow creeps to the top of the hate list (this will be apparent when the NPC turns and starts attacking them instead of fleeing), re-establish aggro and continue.<br><br>Flash of Light has a maximum Fear radius, in this respect.  If an NPC is running away from you, and your partner is killing it, at a certain distance the NPC will aggro your partner, no matter what.  The important thing to do here is to cast Flash of Light, move a little closer to the NPC, and sit.  As it moves away, stand up again, get closer, and sit.  As long as you always manage to stay within 200 feet or so of the NPC, this tactic will work without fail.<br><br>The only other different between this and Fear kiting is that Feared mobs cannot summon - these can.<br><br><font color="ff3333"><li><b>Fear (Defensive)</b></li></font><br><br>Flash of Light may also be used as an emergency defense spell.  If you're fighting and 4 things attack your party, Flash of Light them.  This will allow your group a clean escape - making it harder for the NPC's to catch up on the way out.<br><br>This technique also works while soloing.  If you are hunting outdoors, and you find yourself being defeated in a difficult battle, cast Flash of Light and back off.  While the NPC runs around blinded, you can med, heal, or rebuff as needed.  If Flash wears off, simply cast it again.  This costs much less mana than Rooting the NPC - and casts much faster.<br><br><font color="ff3333"><li><b>PvP</b></li></font><br><br>Lastly, and obviously, Flash of Light works in PvP.  It doesn't have the same taunt effect on a player as it would on an NPC, but it does make the opponent's screen go black.  If they can't see you, it'll be a lot harder for them to hit you.</ol> <p><font color="0000aa"><h5>Vladimirr D'Benefiece<br>Officer, Order of the White Dragon<br>Deepwater Knight<br>In Service of our Good and Gracious Oceanlord, Prexus<br>Bristlebane Server<br><a href = "http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=17434">Click here for equipment listing</a><br></h5></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uvladimirrdbenefiece.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Vladimirr DBenefiece</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.execpc.com/~jwnrski/shield.gif" BORDER=0> at: 4/4/02 6:38:56 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uchavr.showPublicProfile?language=EN>chavr</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Noble Squire</span><br>  Posts: 97<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(4/3/02 7:30:35 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fpaladinsofnorrathgeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=15143.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: aye!</span><hr size=1> Only thing I've really found this useful for is the velium hounds in WW.  They can't be rooted or snared so if one gets on you you have to kill it or try to outrun it.  They are faster then jboots though.  I fol them and it gives me the hea